  abstract   = {This paper presents the operation of tangential 
                dilation, which describes the touching of differentiable 
                surfaces.  It generalizes the classical dilation, but is 
                invertible. It is shown that line segments are eigenfunctions 
                of this dilation, and are parallel-transported, and that 
                curvature is additive. We then present the slope transform 
                which is a re-representation of morphology onto the morphological
                eigenfunctions. As such, the slope transform provides for 
                tangential morphology the same analytical power as the Fourier 
                transform provides for linear signal processing. Under the 
                slope transform dilation becomes addition (just as under a 
                Fourier transform, convolution becomes multiplication). We 
                give a discrete slope transform suited for implementation, 
